---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import QuickAnswer from '../components/QuickAnswer.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import BreadcrumbSchema from '../components/schema/BreadcrumbSchema.astro';
import PersonSchema from '../components/schema/PersonSchema.astro';
import FAQPageSchema from '../components/schema/FAQPageSchema.astro';
import { SITE } from '../consts';

const pressFaqs = [
  {
    q: 'What is Pour Picks?',
    a: 'Pour Picks is an iOS app for adult bourbon collectors. It scans any bottle using AI to read the label, builds a private cellar of what you own, tracks collection value, and recommends what to pour from your own shelf via the "Pour Tonight" feature. The core app is free; an optional Cask Club subscription adds advanced cellar and journaling features.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Who is the founder of Pour Picks?',
    a: 'Pour Picks was founded and built by Bob Guillow, an independent solo developer. The app is published by Timberline Ventures LLC, a single-member LLC. There is no outside investment and no parent company.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What makes Pour Picks different from other whiskey apps?',
    a: 'Most bourbon apps are review aggregators or retail marketplaces. Pour Picks is built around the collector\'s own cellar, not the broader community. The recommender reads from your shelf, not a global rankings list, and the app sells no data, shows no ads, and has no purchase links. It is the only major bourbon app with an AI label scanner and a "Pour Tonight" recommender that works from inventory you already own.',
  },
];

const quickAnswer =
  'Pour Picks is a solo-built iOS app for bourbon collectors. ' +
  'It launched on the App Store on May 9, 2026. ' +
  'Fact sheet, ready-to-quote boilerplate, and contact are all on this page. ' +
  'Brand assets and screenshots are available on request at ' + SITE.supportEmail + '.';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Press"
  description="Press kit for Pour Picks - fact sheet, boilerplate, and brand asset contact for journalists, podcasters, and reviewers."
  path="/press"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <PersonSchema />
    <FAQPageSchema faqs={pressFaqs} />
    <BreadcrumbSchema crumbs={[{ name: 'Press', url: `${SITE.url}/press` }]} />
  </Fragment>

  <p class="brand">{SITE.name}</p>
  <h1>Press Kit</h1>
  <p class="effective">Everything a writer, podcaster, or reviewer needs to cover Pour Picks accurately.</p>

  <QuickAnswer text={quickAnswer} />

  <h2>One-line description</h2>
  <p>
    Pour Picks is the iOS cellar app for bourbon collectors: scan any bottle,
    AI reads the label, and the app builds a private cellar of what you own,
    what you've poured, and what your collection is worth.
  </p>

  <h2>Fact sheet</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Product name:</strong> Pour Picks</li>
    <li><strong>Tagline:</strong> {SITE.tagline}</li>
    <li><strong>Category:</strong> Bourbon and American whiskey cellar app (iOS, free with optional subscription)</li>
    <li><strong>Platform:</strong> iOS (iPhone). iPad and Android are not on the near-term roadmap.</li>
    <li><strong>App Store launch date:</strong> May 9, 2026</li>
    <li><strong>Team:</strong> Independently built and operated. Solo developer.</li>
    <li><strong>Funding:</strong> Bootstrapped. No outside investment, no parent company, no advertising partners.</li>
    <li><strong>Business model:</strong> Free core app. Cask Club subscription adds advanced cellar tracking and journaling. Subscriptions are billed through Apple.</li>
    <li><strong>Catalog size:</strong> Around 4,700 American whiskeys at launch, growing through scan-driven corrections and additions.</li>
    <li><strong>What's distinctive:</strong> Pour Tonight, a recommender that picks a bottle from the user's own cellar and explains why, rather than recommending purchases.</li>
    <li><strong>What it deliberately is not:</strong> Not a marketplace, not a retailer, not a social network. No alcohol ads, no in-app social feed, no leaderboards.</li>
    <li><strong>Tech stack (for technical writers):</strong> React Native, Expo, Supabase (Postgres with row-level security), Anthropic Claude Vision for the scan engine, Claude for the recommender language.</li>
    <li><strong>Privacy:</strong> No location, health, or financial data is collected by the app. Payment information is held by Apple and never touches Pour Picks servers. See the <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Pour Picks exists</h2>
  <p>
    Most bourbon apps fall into one of two categories. Some are community
    review sites, which are built around what other people think of a bottle.
    Others are general spirits apps that treat bourbon like a category to be
    completed rather than a collection to be lived with. Neither answers the
    question a collector actually asks most nights, which is "what should I
    pour from what I already own."
  </p>
  <p>
    Pour Picks is designed around that question. Your cellar is the center
    of the app, not the catalog. The recommender reads from your shelf, not
    from a global rankings list. There are no purchase links, no allocation
    leaderboards, and nothing that nudges you to drink more than you wanted
    to.
  </p>

  <h2>Boilerplate (paste-ready)</h2>
  <p>Short form, around 30 words:</p>
  <blockquote>
    Pour Picks is an iOS app for bourbon collectors that scans any bottle,
    builds a private cellar, and recommends what to pour from what you
    already own. It launched in May 2026.
  </blockquote>

  <p>Medium form, around 60 words:</p>
  <blockquote>
    Pour Picks is a solo-built iOS app for adult bourbon collectors. Scan
    any bottle and an AI reads the label, builds your cellar, and tracks
    every pour. A "Pour Tonight" feature picks a bottle from your own
    shelf and tells you why. The app is free, with an optional Cask Club
    subscription for advanced features. It launched on the App Store in
    May 2026.
  </blockquote>

  <p>Long form, around 110 words:</p>
  <blockquote>
    Pour Picks is an iOS cellar app for adult bourbon collectors, launched
    on the App Store in May 2026 by an independent solo developer.
    The app scans any bottle using Claude Vision to read the label, builds
    a private cellar of what the user owns, and runs a "Pour Tonight"
    recommender that picks a bottle from the user's own shelf based on what
    they've poured recently, the time of year, and personal taste signals.
    The catalog covers roughly 4,700 American whiskeys and grows through
    scan-driven corrections. Pour Picks is bootstrapped, sells no data,
    shows no ads, and does not sell alcohol. The core app is free; an
    optional Cask Club subscription adds advanced cellar features.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Brand assets</h2>
  <p>
    High-resolution app icon, App Store screenshots, hero images, and
    founder headshot are available on request. Email
    <a href={`mailto:${SITE.supportEmail}`}>{SITE.supportEmail}</a> with
    "Press assets" in the subject and a Drive link will follow the same
    day. App Store screenshots can also be pulled directly from the
    <a href={SITE.appStoreUrl} rel="noopener">App Store listing</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Reviewer access</h2>
  <p>
    Any journalist, podcaster, or reviewer who wants to spend real time
    with the app gets a full year of the Cask Club paid tier on the house.
    Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.supportEmail}`}>{SITE.supportEmail}</a>
    with the email tied to your App Store account and the comp is set up
    the same day. There's no expectation of coverage attached, and honest
    takes (including harsh ones) are welcomed.
  </p>

  <h2>Quick links</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>App Store listing: <a href={SITE.appStoreUrl} rel="noopener">{SITE.appStoreUrl}</a></li>
    <li>Web home: <a href={SITE.url}>{SITE.url}</a></li>
    <li>About page (canonical company info): <a href="/about">/about</a></li>
    <li>Articles and editorial: <a href="/articles">/articles</a></li>
    <li>Privacy policy: <a href="/privacy">/privacy</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Press, partnership, podcast, and review inquiries:
    <a href={`mailto:${SITE.supportEmail}`}>{SITE.supportEmail}</a>.
    Email is the canonical contact; replies usually arrive within a day.
  </p>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
